The section on poor community aptly describes what I feel towards Stackexchange and Wikipedia. But I still participate. Maybe less enthusiastically than before, and avoiding the authoritarian feedback, but I still write and vote. Simple answers to stupid questions are still useful. I will learn or not, on my own terms. Not every question needs to be a learning experience. But poor community bites. üôÅ

[new]
Now and then I stumble upon thoughts like this:

‚ÄúI don‚Äôt chase reputation points any longer: it interferes with the writing of a good answer.‚Äù ‚Äì Borodin [¬π](http://stackoverflow.com/questions/19234209/perl-subroutine-arguments)

But then I start thinking ‚Äì how can we undo this mess? It is very unlikely that someone running Stackoverflow will decide to make it better, these guys are doing their business there. If they wanted it to be good they wouldn‚Äôt implement their score-based system. First of all, they need something that attracts users in any way, and a game-like experience works best right now. Great for them.

But since the whole thing will become a big pile of mess eventually, they will probably start **deleting old answers**. Yeah. Since they have a stable flow of questions (which are repeated over and over) this is not a big problem for them ‚Äì every question out there still will have an answer. If not ‚Äì ask it again and get an answer. And this kinda makes sense, in their system, improving old answers is hard and not appreciated. Therefore deleting old answers will solve _everything_.

Do you think that deleting old answers is OK? Or can you see any other way to keep their income without doing that?

But for the moment, let‚Äôs list mentioned emacswiki problems (copied from this page!):

1. The pages are confusing.
2. The code snippets are wrong.
3. The site is badly organized.
4. The information is out of date.

What about stackoverflow?

1. The pages are confusing. ‚Äì One page has a question and a bunch of answers. Every answer answers the same question. You don‚Äôt know which one is better, there is a scoring system but it does not always reflect the quality. Even worse, new answers are placed on top (like if they were somehow better), but later they fall down anyway (like if they became worse or what? Of course, they are trying to fix their lack of Recent Changes by doing that, but maybe implementing Recent Changes can fix their lack of Recent Changes?). Some pages have useful answers but are locked (you cannot contribute and fix problems even if you want to). Some pages are turned into something weird, where every contributor name is hidden. It is called ‚Äúcommunity wiki‚Äù. WTF is that I still don‚Äôt know. However, it works OK most of the time, but that‚Äôs pretty confusing, don‚Äôt you think?
2. The code snippets are wrong. ‚Äì yes, the code snippets are wrong. For example, think about Bash answers ‚Äì instead of giving a link to well written wikis people write their own shitty code. Most of the time, these snippets have errors. It is not better with other languages ‚Äì although these answers _might_ work, the solutions are frequently very ugly.
3. The site is badly organized. ‚Äì not organized _at all_.
4. The information is out of date. ‚Äì yes. Some of the stuff is already out of date, but we will see it becoming much worse a bit later. Stackoverflow is very young, not enough time has passed until we can say ‚Äúit is out of date‚Äù, but there is nothing else you can expect from a system that does not encourage improvements and refactoring _by design_.

There are many bad things our mankind has went through. We will manage to go over this one as well, eventually.

‚Äì [AlexDaniel](http://alexdaniel.org/About) 2015-04-23 00:02 UTC

[new]
Perhaps you are right and eventually Stackoverflow will degenerate into a ‚Äúworse is better‚Äù than [Usenet](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Usenet "Wikipedia"). Old answers will disappear. The same questions will be asked again and again. But at least we‚Äôll have rudimentary scoring. Perhaps this would be a simple thing for a wiki to add. Like little +1 or _I like_ buttons ‚Äì but for every section, or paragraph, or code snippet. Essentially, this would make it easier for people to keep the good stuff and delete the useless stuff.

